7. List Element
->1. Ordered List   -> <ol> tag defines an ordered list
->2. Unordered List -> <ul> tag defines an unordered (bulleted) list

->3. <li> HTML element
->li-Listed items 
->items in list are wirriten in <li> tags.
->The <li> HTML element is used to represent an item  in a list.

eg:
<ol>
    <li>Code</li>
    <li>Reading Books</li>
<ol>

8. The Anchor Element
The <a> HTML element (or anchor element), with its href attribute, creates a hyperlink to web pages, files, email addresses, locations in the same page, or anything else a URL can address.

eg:
 <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/feed/">linkedin</a>

9. Attribute In HTML
 ->Attributes provide additional information about elements 

10. Linking Pages In HTML
eg:
<a href="05-About.html">About Me</a>
<a href="04-HTML Boilerplate.html">Home</a>

11. Inserting link in Content

eg:
<p>
        Tennis is a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Racket_(sports_equipment)">racket</a> sport that is played either individually against a single opponent (singles) or between
        two teams of two players each (doubles). or around a net and into the opponent's court.
</p>

12. Image Element
The <img> HTML element embeds an image into the document.
->
->Locating image from desktop
<img src="./tennis.jpg" alt="" width="200" height="300">
->Locating image in internet
<img src="https://plus.unsplash.com/premium_photo-1673995612206-346b49f789cc?ixlib=rb-4.0.3&ixid=MnwxMjA3fDB8MHxzZWFyY2h8MXx8dGVubmlzfGVufDB8fDB8fA%3D%3D&auto=format&fit=crop&w=1000&q=60" alt="" width="200" height="300">

->Lable the image in alt if image is not in located folder or located address it shows that label.
<img src="./tennis.jp" alt="tennis" width="200" height="300">

13. Alt attribte
->alt attribute will be read by screen reader.
->alt attributes holds a text description of the image.
->which isn't mandatory but is incredibly useful for 
access.








